		  was carried out in 5 × 5 m outdoor enclosures to quantify
		  phytochemical changes of either endophyte-infected (E+) or
		  endophyte-free (E-) meadow fescue (Schedonorus pratensis)
		  in response to medium intensity (corresponding with
		  densities of ca. 1200 voles / ha for 5 weeks during 3
		  months) or heavy intensity (ca. 1200 voles / ha for 8 weeks
		  during 3 months) grazing by a mammalian herbivore, the
		  field vole (Microtus agrestis). A laboratory experiment was
		  then conducted to evaluate the effects of endophyte
		  infection status and grazing history of the grass diet on
		  vole performance. As predicted, grazing increased foliar
		  silicon content, by up to 13 \%. Grazing also increased
		  foliar levels of phosphorous and several phenolic
		  compounds, most notably those of the flavonols
		  isorhamnetin-diglycoside and rhamnetin derivative. Silicon
		  concentrations were consistently circa 16 \% higher in E+
